Depression in men rarely looks like the commercials. It looks like getting up, going to work, coming home, and feeling nothing. It looks like losing interest in things that used to fire you up. It looks like a short fuse, a long silence, one more beer, another night scrolling until you're tired enough to sleep. From the outside you're functioning. Inside, somebody dimmed the lights.

A lot of men live like this for years, because it doesn't feel like an emergency. It just feels gray.

## What's actually going on

Depression flattens more than mood — it flattens meaning. The things that are supposed to matter stop registering. And for men, that often gets tangled with shame: *I have a good life, why can't I feel it? What's wrong with me?* So you hide it, manage appearances, and the isolation feeds the very thing that's draining you.

Sometimes there's a clear trigger — a loss, a failure, a season of relentless stress. Sometimes it crept in so slowly you can't name a start date. Either way, it's real, it's common in men, and it responds to real work.

## How counseling helps

We start by taking honest inventory — what's dimmed, when it dimmed, and what the weight is actually made of. Often there's unprocessed material underneath: grief that never got its turn, anger swallowed for years, a story that says your worth is your output. We work through that at the root, not just at the symptom level.

And we do it within a bigger story. The Christian faith has never pretended the valley doesn't exist — it says the valley is real *and* it isn't the end of the road. Hope, in this office, isn't a greeting-card word. It's the working assumption.

## When to reach out

If you've been flat, checked out, or running on fumes for more than a few weeks — or if the people around you have started asking what's wrong — it's time. If you're having thoughts of ending your life, don't wait for an appointment: call or text 988 now.
